# Function to clean tweets
def clean_tweets(tweet):
    tweet = re.sub("@[A-Za-z0-9]+", "", tweet)  # Remove @mentions
    tweet = re.sub(r"https?\:\/\/[\w\.\/]+", "", tweet)  # Remove URLs
    tweet = re.sub(r"[^A-Za-z0-9 ]+", "", tweet)  # Remove all non-alphanumeric characters except spaces
    tweet = tweet.lower()  # Convert to lowercase to avoid duplicates from capitalization
    tweet = " ".join(tweet.split())  # Remove redundant spaces
    return tweet

# Apply the cleaning function to each tweet in the DataFrames
for name, df in dataframes.items():
    df['cleaned_body'] = df['body'].apply(clean_tweets)

# Printing the new sizes of the DataFrames after cleaning
print("New sizes of dataframes after cleaning:")
for name, df in dataframes.items():
    print(f"{name}: {df.shape}")

# Prepare the list of tokenized tweets for Word2Vec training
# Concatenate all tweets from different datasets into a single list for training
all_tweets = []
for name, df in dataframes.items():
    all_tweets.extend(df['cleaned_body'].apply(lambda x: x.split()).tolist())

# Train a Word2Vec model
word2vec_model = Word2Vec(sentences=all_tweets, vector_size=100, window=5, min_count=1, workers=4)

# Save the model for later use
word2vec_model.save("/content/drive/My Drive/519_Project_V1/LSTM/word2vec_model.bin")

# Check the word vector for a sample word to ensure training
print("Vector for the word 'tesla':")
print(word2vec_model.wv['tesla'])

# Function to vectorize a batch of tweets
def vectorize_tweets(tweets, word2vec_model, max_length):
    vectorized_tweets = []
    for tweet in tweets:
        tweet_vector = [word2vec_model.wv[word] for word in tweet if word in word2vec_model.wv]
        vectorized_tweets.append(tweet_vector)

    # Pad the sequences to have the same length
    vectorized_tweets = pad_sequences(vectorized_tweets, maxlen=max_length, dtype='float32', padding='post', truncating='post', value=0.0)
    return vectorized_tweets

# Define the maximum length of a tweet vector sequence
max_length = 50  # Adjust based on the average length of your tweets

# Vectorize the tweets in each DataFrame and store them
vectorized_dataframes = {}
for name, df in dataframes.items():
    tokenized_tweets = df['cleaned_body'].apply(lambda x: x.split()).tolist()
    vectorized_dataframes[name] = vectorize_tweets(tokenized_tweets, word2vec_model, max_length)

# Print shapes of the vectorized data
for name, vectors in vectorized_dataframes.items():
    print(f"Vectorized data for {name}: {vectors.shape}")

# Define the optimized LSTM model function
def create_optimized_lstm_model(input_shape):
    model = Sequential()

    # LSTM layer with 64 units
    model.add(LSTM(64, return_sequences=True, input_shape=input_shape))
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))

    # Another LSTM layer with 64 units, without return_sequences to flatten the output
    model.add(LSTM(64))
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))

    # Dense layer for the output
    model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))  # Use sigmoid for binary classification

    # Compile the model with a specified learning rate
    optimizer = Adam(learning_rate=0.0005)
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

    return model

# Function to evaluate the model
def evaluate_model(model, X_test, y_test):
    # Predict the labels for the test set
    y_pred = (model.predict(X_test) > 0.5).astype("int32")

    # Calculate evaluation metrics
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)

    return accuracy, precision, recall, f1

# Dictionary to store performance metrics
optimized_performance_metrics = {}

# Use the shape of the vectorized data to define the input shape for the LSTM model
input_shape = (vectorized_dataframes['train_data_w'].shape[1], vectorized_dataframes['train_data_w'].shape[2])

# Create the optimized LSTM model using the defined function
optimized_lstm_model = create_optimized_lstm_model(input_shape)

# Print the model summary to review the architecture
optimized_lstm_model.summary()

# Train and evaluate for each dataset
for key in ['train_data_w', 'train_data_m', 'train_data_q']:
    train_key = key
    test_key = key.replace('train', 'test')

    X_train = vectorized_dataframes[train_key]
    y_train = dataframes[train_key]['Target'].values
    X_test = vectorized_dataframes[test_key]
    y_test = dataframes[test_key]['Target'].values

    # Train the model with EarlyStopping for better generalization
    early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_accuracy', patience=3, restore_best_weights=True)
    optimized_lstm_model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=5, batch_size=32, validation_split=0.2, callbacks=[early_stopping])

    # Evaluate the model
    accuracy, precision, recall, f1 = evaluate_model(optimized_lstm_model, X_test, y_test)

    # Store the metrics
    optimized_performance_metrics[test_key] = {
        'Accuracy': accuracy,

        'Recall': recall,
        'F1 Score': f1

def train_and_save_model(train_data, test_data, model_name):
    X_train = vectorized_dataframes[train_data]
    y_train = dataframes[train_data]['Target'].values
    X_test = vectorized_dataframes[test_data]
    y_test = dataframes[test_data]['Target'].values

    model = create_optimized_lstm_model(input_shape)

    model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=5, batch_size=32, validation_split=0.2, callbacks=[early_stopping])

    # Save the trained model
    model.save(f'/content/drive/My Drive/519_Project_V1/LSTM/{model_name}.h5')

from tensorflow.keras.utils import plot_model
from IPython.display import Image

# Function to print and display the model architecture
def print_and_display_model(model_path, model_name):
    # Load the model
    model = tf.keras.models.load_model(model_path)

    # Print the model summary
    print(f"Model Summary for {model_name}:")
    model.summary()

    # Generate and save the model architecture diagram
    plot_path = f'/content/drive/My Drive/519_Project_V1/LSTM/{model_name}_architecture.png'
    plot_model(model, to_file=plot_path, show_shapes=True, show_layer_names=True)

    # Display the model architecture image
    print(f"Model Architecture for {model_name}:")
    display(Image(plot_path))

# Print and display the architecture for the weekly model
print_and_display_model('/content/drive/My Drive/519_Project_V1/LSTM/model_weekly.h5', 'Weekly Model')

# Print and display the architecture for the monthly model
print_and_display_model('/content/drive/My Drive/519_Project_V1/LSTM/model_monthly.h5', 'Monthly Model')

# Print and display the architecture for the quarterly model
print_and_display_model('/content/drive/My Drive/519_Project_V1/LSTM/model_quarterly.h5', 'Quarterly Model')
